<h2 style="color:blue">
<a name="TOC-New-capabilities"></a>
New capabilities:
</h2>
<br/><br/>

<apex:image url="{!$Resource.PRIOtopbuttons}" styleClass="floatRight" />
<h3>
<a name="TOC-See-More-Do-More"></a>
See More, Do More
</h3>

<p>
The new Prioritizer features a tiled UI: your prioritized backlog on the left, with an unranked list of items in the right-hand Backburner tile, plus a filter tile in the middle. You can choose which tiles to show/hide with just one click of the tile selector buttons at the top of the page. You don't have to look at your unranked items if you don't want to, just close the tile anytime with one click.
</p>

<br/><br/>
<apex:image url="{!$Resource.PRIOtopofbackburner}" styleClass="floatLeft" />
<a name="TOC-What-s-on-Top"></a>
<h3>What's on Top</h3>

<p>
The new Prioritizer keeps your top-ranked work at the top of your Backlog tile, where it belongs. Meanwhile, new Work items for your team-- maybe things you haven't sized, reviewed, or even decided for sure to do-- go straight to the new Backburner tile of unranked items. There's no need to drag-and-drop them out of your way anymore, now you can choose to drag them into the backlog whenever you're ready.
</p>

<br/><br/>
<a name="TOC-Rank-in-Real-Time"></a>
<h3>Rank in Real-Time</h3>

<p>
 Drag-and-drop items up and down the backlog, and into and out of the Backlog and Backburner tile-- your changes will be saved in real-time, no need for an extra "Save" click!
</p>

<a name="TOC-Check-Your-Velocity"></a>
<h3>Check Your Velocity</h3>
<apex:image url="{!$Resource.PRIOtopofbackburner}" styleClass="floatRight" />
<p>
At a glance, the new Prioritizer gives you an idea of what you can fit in each sprint: The new Prioritizer knows your velocity, and places a light blue line within your backlog where one sprint's worth of work might fall, based on the story points you've assigned to your work. It's just a guide-- you're still free to place items in any sprint you want. And you can change the number of sprints-worth of data GUS uses to make its calculations, by clicking on the wrench icon in the upper right of the page. In the future, we'll enable a complete manual override of your known velocity. 
</p>

<a name="TOC-Story-Point-in-No-Time"></a>
<h3>
Story Point in No Time
</h3>

<p>
One-click story-pointing: every row in the Prioritizer now includes a picklist of your team's story point values, and saves your selections in real-time. The amount of clicks needed to story-point an item from the Prioritizer has dropped from four (+ a bonus drag), to one!
</p>

<a name="TOC-Focus-on-What-Matters"></a>
<h3>
Focus On What Matters
</h3>
<apex:image url="{!$Resource.PRIOfilterbybuild2}" styleClass="floatLeft" />
<p>
As part of the new tiled interface, the new Prioritizer includes a Filter tile that lets you select items from within your backlog, as well as from within your unranked backburner items, and focus on them exclusively, using criteria of Build, Sprint, or Theme. You can change filter criteria any time by clicking the wrench at the top of the tile. In the future, you'll also be able to re-rank items within this Filter tile, plus have other filter criteria options. The filter tile will never offer complete parity with an enhanced list view-- still the GUS Team's recommended tool for mass editing and filtering of any object-- but having some of these capabilities right on the Prioritizer can save a lot of clicks.
</p>

<br/><br/>
<a name="TOC-Have-Edits-Will-Not-Travel"></a>
<h3>
Have Edits, Will Not Travel
</h3>
<apex:image url="{!$Resource.PRIOrowdropdown}" styleClass="floatRight" />
<p>
Now you can edit the Subject, Status and Description of Work records straight from the Prioritizer-- no more clicking out to the full record detail. The number of clicks needed to edit a subject drops from 4-and-ouch-a-browser-refresh, to 3.
</p>

<a name="TOC-Trim-Your-Backlog"></a>
<h3>
Trim Your Backlog
</h3>

<p>
In the old Prioritizer, if you saw something there you wanted to close out, or "Never," you had to click through to the item, make your edits, then come back to the Prioritizer and refresh via the browser. Now, with a real-time editable Status picklist, when you select any closed status values, the item is removed instantly.
</p>

<a name="TOC-And-oh-yeah-it-s-faster"></a>
<h3>
And oh yeah it's faster!
</h3>

<p>
We like faster.
</p>

<a name="TOC-What-stayed-the-same"></a>
<h2 style="color:blue">
What stayed the same:
</h2>
<br/><br/>
<a name="TOC-Mass-assign-Scheduled-Build-Sprint"></a>
<h3>
Mass-assign Scheduled Build, Sprint, and Theme
</h3>
<apex:image url="{!$Resource.PRIOmassedits}" styleClass="floatRight" />

The familiar functionality from the old Prioritizer, where you select as many items as you like (now via checkbox), and then apply a new Build, Sprint, or Theme value via lookup links at the top of the page, works almost exactly the same in the new Prioritizer, with the added enhancement that the autocomplete lookup now works from anywhere in a string, not just the beginning: So if you type "72.6," 172.6 will appear as an option just as if you'd typed the whole thing.

<br/><br/>

<a name="TOC-Full-Column-View">Full Column View"></a>
<h3>
Full Column View
</h3>

<p>
The old Prioritizer showed you the Build, Sprint, and Theme values as columns on the right-side of the page. In any multi-tile view on the new Prioritizer, these are hidden. But go down to 1 tile, and they re-appear, for a sort of Prioritizer-classic view.
</p>

<a name="TOC-How-to-Make-It-on-the-Prioritizer"></a>
<h3>
How to Make It on the Prioritizer
</h3>

<p>
Any GUS Work of record types Bug, User Story, and ToDo can be included in the Prioritizer, as long as its "Include in Prioritize View" box is checked. This is also mass-editable via an enhanced list view, if you want to move many items on/off the Prioritizer at once.
</p>

