The Old Prioritizer
</h3>
<p>
It's passed on! The old Prioritizer is no more! It has ceased to be! It's expired and gone to meet its maker! It's a stiff! Bereft of life, it rests in peace! If we didn't nail it to the perch it'd be pushing up the daisies! Its metabolic processes are now history! It's off the twig! It's kicked the bucket, it's shuffled off its mortal coil, run down the curtain and joined the choir invisibile! THIS IS AN EX-PRIORITIZER!
</p>

<a name="TOC-The-New-Work-Button"></a>
<h3>
The "New Work" Button
</h3>
<p>
But it'll come back someday!
</p>

<a name="TOC-Mass-Drag-and-Drop-Re-Ranking"></a>
<h3>
Mass Drag-and-Drop Re-Ranking
</h3>

<p>
Also on a list of future enhancements for the new Prioritizer, the former ability to select multiple items at a time, and rank them in the same new spot, is no longer available. As a temporary workaround, an enhanced list view can set multiple ranks at a time. Generally, the new Prioritizer will continue to favor enhancements aimed at planning capabilities, with some more purely mass-edit functions left to list views, though this is one piece of functionality that will be brought back.
</p>

<a name="TOC-The-Story-Pointing-Button"></a>
<h3>
The Story Pointing Button
</h3>

<p>
And its nifty little screen to assign story points. Who needs its clicky goodness, when every record can have its points set with just one click? Even if you need to point three items at once, the number of clicks required has dropped from six (+ three bonus drags) to three!
</p>

<a name="TOC-The-Save-Reset-Buttons"></a>
<h3>
The Save/Reset Buttons
</h3>

<p>
Drag-and-Drop re-ranking is now saved in real-time, and individual rows are saved locally, so no global Save/Reset is needed anymore!
</p>

<a name="TOC-Some-Scrolling"></a>
<h3>
Some Scrolling
</h3>

<p>
By default the new Prioritizer loads 50 records per tile, instead of 200 as before. You can always click "Show More" if you need to see more, but you may find that you're able to use the multi-tile interface to view things side-by-side, and reduce scrolling dramatically.
</p>

<a name="TOC-The-Priority-Column"></a>
<h3>
The Priority Column
</h3>
<p>
No, not that one! The P1, P2, etc. column. Used more for bugs, the GUS Team can consider adding it back depending on usage patterns.
</p>

